<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="206" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1707,1984]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,317,1851,1876]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">Remarks:</emphasis>
This new species is similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Dworakowska" authorityName="Dworakowska" authorityYear="1977" box="[683,980,1851,1876]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Anufrievia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="206" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="cervena">
<emphasis box="[683,805,1852,1875]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">A. cervena</emphasis>
Dworakowska
</taxonomicName>
, but can be distinguished by bifurcated apex of style, straight pygofer dorsal appendage, and the shortened part of aedeagus from gonopore to apex.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="206" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,1707,1984]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1923,1948]" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">Etymology:</emphasis>
The specific epithet is derived from the Latin word “ 
<emphasis box="[965,1062,1924,1947]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="206">arcuatus</emphasis>
”, referring to the hooked apical processes of aedeagal shaft.
</paragraph>
